<!-- ================= MAIN ================= -->
<div class="main">
  <div class="topbar">
    <h1 id="page-title">Overview &amp; Method</h1>
    <div class="meta">Applicable to any energy supply situation<br>Validation case: <b>2026 Iran war / Strait of Hormuz</b></div>
  </div>
  <div class="status-banner">
    <span class="pill">Purpose</span>
    <span>A <b>crisis-agnostic analytical instrument</b>: five scientific methods, a standing indicator set, an early-warning monitor and a probabilistic scenario engine that can be applied to any energy supply disruption, whether geopolitical (chokepoints, sanctions, war), technical (infrastructure failure, cyber), or natural (weather, disaster). The 2026 Iran war serves as the empirical validation case.</span>
  </div>

  <div class="content">

    <!-- ============================================================ OVERVIEW -->
    <section class="tab-panel active" id="tab-overview">

      <h2 class="section-title">The Scientific Workflow</h2>
      <p class="lede">
        The framework follows the scientific method as a repeatable analytical cycle. Every energy situation, regardless of its trigger, is processed through the same six steps. This enforces discipline: hypotheses are stated before data are interpreted, predictions are made before outcomes are known, and probabilities are updated against pre-specified triggers rather than headlines.
      </p>
      <div class="pipeline">
        <div class="pipe-step"><div class="p-num">1</div><h4>Observe</h4><p>Collect standardized indicators: flows, prices, inventories, transit data, policy events.</p></div>
        <div class="pipe-step"><div class="p-num">2</div><h4>Hypothesize</h4><p>State a falsifiable proposition, e.g. "the disruption removes X% of supply for Y weeks".</p></div>
        <div class="pipe-step"><div class="p-num">3</div><h4>Model</h4><p>Apply the five methods independently; each produces its own estimate and confidence.</p></div>
        <div class="pipe-step"><div class="p-num">4</div><h4>Predict</h4><p>Publish scenario paths with explicit probabilities and a defined forecast horizon.</p></div>
        <div class="pipe-step"><div class="p-num">5</div><h4>Test</h4><p>Compare realized outcomes to predictions at fixed checkpoints; measure forecast error.</p></div>
        <div class="pipe-step"><div class="p-num">6</div><h4>Update</h4><p>Revise probabilities Bayesian-style when pre-agreed triggers fire; document each revision.</p></div>
      </div>

      <h2 class="section-title">Universal Indicator Set: Definitions, 5-Year Series &amp; Predictive Skill (Jul 2021 – Jul 2026)</h2>
      <p class="lede">
        Nine standardized indicators describe any energy situation: six core indicators plus three extended indicators added because real public data exist for them. When a new situation begins, only the values change, never the structure. The five-year window covers five distinct regimes: the post-COVID recovery and 2021 gas squeeze, the 2022 Russia-Ukraine energy crisis, the 2023 disinflation, the 2024 Red Sea disruption and brief June 2025 Israel-Iran conflict, and the 2026 Iran war. <b>Data status is marked per indicator.</b> Six indicators are built from real published series: the Price Deviation Index (EIA/FRED Brent), the Inflation Impulse (BLS CPI and Eurostat HICP energy components), the Redundancy Ratio (EIA STEO spare capacity, approximated), the Gas Price Deviation Index (ICE TTF benchmark), the Geopolitical Risk Index (Caldara-Iacoviello GPR, a public academic series), and the EU Gas Storage Deviation (GIE AGSI+ transparency platform). Three indicators require commercial feeds and are therefore defined but not plotted: Supply at Risk, Logistics Stress, and Risk Premium. The framework does not display illustrative series; their charts and skill panels activate once real feeds supply the inputs.
        <b>The predictive skill panels are computed backtests and are shown only for the real-data indicators:</b> each applies a stated mechanical decision rule to its series and measures the rolling 12-month share of correct one-month-ahead directional calls against a stated target (Brent or TTF), with 50% = no skill. The three commercial-feed indicators carry no skill panel, because a backtest on illustrative inputs would not be a meaningful measurement; their panels will be activated once real feeds replace the inputs. Notes: real-data series are compiled from published figures rather than a live API; the US CPI has a gap in October&ndash;November 2025 (lapse in appropriations); values there and for the most recent months pending release are interpolated estimates, and GPR/TTF/storage values are transcribed to monthly precision.
      </p>
      <div class="grid g3">
        <div class="card">
          <h3>Price Deviation Index <span class="badge low">Real data</span></h3>
          <div class="chart-box" style="height:200px;"><canvas id="hist-pdi"></canvas></div>
          <span class="src">Brent monthly averages (EIA STEO/FRED, compiled from published figures) ÷ pre-2026-event baseline ($71) × 100. Five regimes visible: the 2021 recovery, the 2022 Russia shock (peak ~166 in June 2022), the 2023 disinflation, the soft 2024&ndash;25 drift, and the 2026 shock (April monthly average $117, index ~165; daily peak $138 on 7 April, index ~194) with retracement to ~$70 by 1 July and a renewed jump toward $78 on the 7&ndash;8 July re-escalation.</span>
          <div class="skill-panel">
            <div class="skill-head"><span class="sk-label">Predictive skill · computed backtest, overall hit rate</span><span class="sk-val" id="skval-pdi">&ndash;</span></div>
            <div class="skill-box"><canvas id="skill-pdi"></canvas></div>
            <span class="src">Computed on the real series. Rule: if the index moved ≥3 points over the past two months, predict the same direction for next month's Brent. Bars show the rolling 12-month share of correct calls; 50% dashed line = no skill. Momentum is largely coincident with price, so skill is modest and concentrated in trending crisis phases.</span>
          </div>
          <div class="def-block">
            <div class="def-row"><span class="def-key">Definition</span><span><code>PDI(t) = P(t) / P(baseline) × 100</code>, where P(t) is the monthly average benchmark price (Brent front-month for oil situations; TTF or JKM for gas situations) and P(baseline) is the 30-trading-day average immediately preceding the event trigger date. Rebasing to 100 makes shocks comparable across commodities and episodes.</span></div>
            <div class="def-row"><span class="def-key">Interpretation</span><span>100 = no deviation. 100&ndash;110 is within normal volatility; &gt;110 indicates a material shock; &gt;140 a severe shock. The peak value defines the amplitude of a crisis; the decay speed measures normalization.</span></div>
            <div class="def-row"><span class="def-key">Data sources</span><span>ICE / EIA daily settlement prices, aggregated to monthly averages.</span></div>
            <div class="def-row"><span class="def-key">Frequency</span><span>Daily during active situations; monthly otherwise.</span></div>
            <div class="def-row"><span class="def-key">Iran 2026</span><span>Baseline $71; April monthly average $117 (index ~165, highest monthly average since June 2022 per EIA); daily peak $138 on 7 April (index ~194); fell below $70 on 1 July, then jumped ~5% to ~$78 on the 7&ndash;8 July re-escalation (index ~110).</span></div>
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="card">
          <h3>Supply at Risk (% of Global Supply) <span class="badge med">Commercial feed required · no chart</span></h3>
          <p style="background:#f7fafc; border:1px dashed #c9d6e2; border-radius:8px; padding:14px; font-size:12px; color:#5a748c;">No series is plotted for this indicator; the framework does not display illustrative reconstructions. <b>What a live feed requires:</b> (1) a Kpler or Vortexa API subscription for crude and product flows by origin, destination and status (commercial license, typically a five-figure annual cost); (2) a documented disruption ruleset defining when a volume counts as "at risk" (blocked, embargoed, damaged, or under enforced threat); (3) a monthly aggregation job dividing tagged volumes by IEA/EIA global supply. Lower-fidelity free alternative: EIA's published disruption estimates, quarterly rather than weekly. Reference points from reporting: 2022 Russia embargo period ~3&ndash;5% exposed; 2026 Hormuz closure ~20% at peak.</p>
          <div class="def-block">
            <div class="def-row"><span class="def-key">Definition</span><span><code>SaR(t) = V(disrupted, t) / V(global, t) × 100</code>, where the numerator is the volume exposed to active disruption (blocked, embargoed, damaged, or under credible threat with demonstrated enforcement) and the denominator is total global supply of the commodity.</span></div>
            <div class="def-row"><span class="def-key">Interpretation</span><span>&lt;2% is background noise; 2&ndash;5% a regional event; 5&ndash;15% a major event; &gt;15% a systemic event requiring full framework activation. The historical maximum is ~20% (Hormuz 2026).</span></div>
            <div class="def-row"><span class="def-key">Data sources</span><span>IEA / EIA supply balances, tanker tracking (Kpler), official export statistics of affected producers.</span></div>
            <div class="def-row"><span class="def-key">Frequency</span><span>Weekly; re-estimated immediately on trigger events.</span></div>
            <div class="def-row"><span class="def-key">Iran 2026</span><span>~20% of global oil trade plus ~20% of LNG exposed via Hormuz; 10&ndash;14 mb/d of exports stranded at peak.</span></div>
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="card">
          <h3>Redundancy Ratio <span class="badge low">Real data (approx.)</span></h3>
          <div class="chart-box" style="height:200px;"><canvas id="hist-rr"></canvas></div>
          <span class="src">Bypass + spare capacity ÷ volume at risk, capped at 1.0. Approximated from EIA STEO spare-capacity assessments and documented disruption volumes: OPEC spare fell to ~2.5&ndash;3 mb/d against ~3&ndash;5 mb/d of Russian exports at risk in 2022 (ratio ~0.6&ndash;0.7), recovered through 2023&ndash;25, and collapsed to ~0.13 in March 2026 (~2.6 mb/d bypass vs. ~20 mb/d at risk).</span>
          <div class="skill-panel">
            <div class="skill-head"><span class="sk-label">Predictive skill · computed backtest, overall hit rate</span><span class="sk-val" id="skval-rr">&ndash;</span></div>
            <div class="skill-box"><canvas id="skill-rr"></canvas></div>
            <span class="src">Computed on the real-approximation series. Rule: signals only when the ratio is below 0.9 (a live constraint); deteriorating ratio predicts Brent up next month, recovering ratio predicts down. The computed hit rate is modest and rests on very few signal months (the ratio binds only during 2022 and 2026), so the sample is too small for strong claims. The ratio's analytical value is amplitude prediction (how severe a shock becomes), which a monthly directional test does not fully capture.</span>
          </div>
          <div class="def-block">
            <div class="def-row"><span class="def-key">Definition</span><span><code>RR(t) = (C(bypass) + C(spare)) / V(at risk)</code>. Bypass capacity covers alternative routes usable within 30 days (pipelines, rerouting, alternative ports); spare capacity follows the IEA definition: production activatable within 30 days and sustainable for 90 days. Displayed capped at 1.0.</span></div>
            <div class="def-row"><span class="def-key">Interpretation</span><span>≥1.0 means the disruption is fully substitutable and price effects stay contained; 0.5&ndash;1.0 partial substitution; &lt;0.3 structural shortage, in which most of the Supply at Risk converts into an actual physical deficit. RR is the single best predictor of a crisis's price amplitude.</span></div>
            <div class="def-row"><span class="def-key">Data sources</span><span>EIA pipeline capacity assessments, OPEC / IEA spare capacity estimates, shipping route feasibility analysis.</span></div>
            <div class="def-row"><span class="def-key">Frequency</span><span>Monthly baseline; re-estimated at event onset.</span></div>
            <div class="def-row"><span class="def-key">Iran 2026</span><span>~0.13 at peak: only ~2.6 mb/d pipeline bypass (Saudi East-West, UAE Fujairah) against ~20 mb/d at risk. This is why Hormuz 2026 was far more severe than the Red Sea 2024 episode despite similar headline attention.</span></div>
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="card">
          <h3>Logistics Stress Index <span class="badge med">Commercial feed required · no chart</span></h3>
          <p style="background:#f7fafc; border:1px dashed #c9d6e2; border-radius:8px; padding:14px; font-size:12px; color:#5a748c;">No series is plotted for this indicator; the framework does not display illustrative reconstructions. <b>What a live feed requires:</b> (1) an AIS vessel-tracking API (Windward, Kpler Marine or MarineTraffic) for corridor transit counts and dwell/stranding detection; (2) Lloyd's List Intelligence for verified stranded-vessel and casualty counts; (3) war-risk insurance premia, which have no API and must be transcribed monthly from broker reporting (Marsh, Gallagher) and trade press. Components (1) and (2) are commercial subscriptions; component (3) is manual effort. Reference points from reporting: peak stress at the March 2026 closure with 600+ vessels stranded and transits down to 5&ndash;11/day.</p>
          <div class="def-block">
            <div class="def-row"><span class="def-key">Definition</span><span>Composite index scaled 0&ndash;100: <code>LSI = 0.4 × transit deviation + 0.3 × stranded vessels + 0.3 × insurance premium</code>. Transit deviation is measured against the trailing 30-day mean of the affected corridor; the stranded-vessel count and war-risk insurance premium are normalized to their worst observation in the sample (= 100).</span></div>
            <div class="def-row"><span class="def-key">Interpretation</span><span>&lt;15 normal operations; 15&ndash;40 elevated friction (higher freight and insurance costs); 40&ndash;70 disrupted (rerouting, delays, selective transit); &gt;70 acute (corridor effectively unusable). LSI typically leads price at turning points because vessels react before settlement prices do.</span></div>
            <div class="def-row"><span class="def-key">Data sources</span><span>AIS vessel tracking (Kpler, Windward), Lloyd's List Intelligence stranded-vessel counts, marine war-risk insurance market reporting, JMIC route notices.</span></div>
            <div class="def-row"><span class="def-key">Frequency</span><span>Daily during active situations; weekly otherwise.</span></div>
            <div class="def-row"><span class="def-key">Iran 2026</span><span>Peak 100 in March: 600+ vessels stranded (incl. 325 tankers), transits down to 5&ndash;11/day, a 230-tanker loading backlog; currently ~40 as traffic recovers under the MoU.</span></div>
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="card">
          <h3>Risk Premium ($/bbl equivalent) <span class="badge med">Commercial feed required · no chart</span></h3>
          <p style="background:#f7fafc; border:1px dashed #c9d6e2; border-radius:8px; padding:14px; font-size:12px; color:#5a748c;">No series is plotted for this indicator; the framework does not display illustrative reconstructions. <b>What a live feed requires:</b> this one is built, not bought. (1) A maintained Method 1 fundamentals model producing a fair-value price from free public inputs (EIA/IEA inventories, spare capacity, demand estimates); (2) daily Brent settlements (free via EIA/FRED); (3) the premium is then simply spot minus model output. The cost is analyst effort to build and recalibrate the model, roughly a small spreadsheet-to-Python project, plus periodic cross-checks against published bank decompositions. Reference points from reporting: ~$14/bbl at the 2026 outbreak (Goldman Sachs), compressed to ~$5&ndash;10 post-MoU.</p>
          <div class="def-block">
            <div class="def-row"><span class="def-key">Definition</span><span><code>RP(t) = P(spot, t) &minus; P(fundamental, t)</code>, where the fundamentals-implied price is produced by the physical balance model of Method 1 (inventories, spare capacity, demand). Expressed in $/bbl for oil situations, €/MWh equivalent for gas. The residual captures the compensation the market demands for disruption risk beyond what current physical balances justify.</span></div>
            <div class="def-row"><span class="def-key">Interpretation</span><span>$2&ndash;5 is the normal background geopolitical premium. A doubling within five sessions fires the Monitor 2 alert. Absent new trigger events, the premium decays with a half-life measured in weeks; persistence signals the market pricing structural rather than episodic risk.</span></div>
            <div class="def-row"><span class="def-key">Data sources</span><span>Method 1 model output plus daily settlements; cross-checked against published bank decompositions (e.g. the Goldman Sachs $14/bbl estimate at the 2026 outbreak).</span></div>
            <div class="def-row"><span class="def-key">Frequency</span><span>Weekly; daily during active situations.</span></div>
            <div class="def-row"><span class="def-key">Iran 2026</span><span>~$14 on day three (Goldman Sachs), estimated $25&ndash;30 at the March peak, compressed to ~$5&ndash;10 after the June MoU, with demonstrated ability to re-inflate within hours (June re-closure).</span></div>
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="card">
          <h3>Inflation Impulse (%, by Region) <span class="badge low">Real data</span></h3>
          <div class="chart-box" style="height:200px;"><canvas id="hist-ii"></canvas></div>
          <span class="src">Energy component contribution to headline inflation, in %: energy YoY × basket weight (US: BLS CPI energy × ~7%; euro area: Eurostat HICP energy × ~9&ndash;10%, 2026 weight 9.0%). Verified anchors: Eurostat puts the euro area energy contribution at +0.98pp in May 2026; the 2022 Russia crisis contribution exceeded +4% at peak (gas channel) vs. ~+2.9% in the US, while 2026 hits the US harder (gasoline channel). 2023&ndash;25 shows the negative (disinflationary) energy contribution. US Oct&ndash;Nov 2025 interpolated (CPI data gap); latest months pending release are estimates.</span>
          <div class="skill-panel">
            <div class="skill-head"><span class="sk-label">Predictive skill · computed backtest, overall hit rate</span><span class="sk-val" id="skval-ii">&ndash;</span></div>
            <div class="skill-box"><canvas id="skill-ii"></canvas></div>
            <span class="src">Computed on the real series (US contribution). Rule: if the contribution rose over the past two months, predict Brent up next month; if it fell, predict down. Expected to hover near the no-skill line: inflation is a lagging indicator that confirms transmission (Method 4 validation), it does not forecast prices. Its low computed score is a feature of the test, not a defect of the data.</span>
          </div>
          <div class="def-block">
            <div class="def-row"><span class="def-key">Definition</span><span><code>II(t) = π(headline, t) &minus; π(counterfactual, t)</code>, the difference between realized headline inflation and the counterfactual path with energy prices frozen at the pre-event baseline, computed per region. First approximation: change in the energy CPI component × its basket weight; structural model estimates (DSGE-VAR, Kilian et al. 2026) are preferred where available.</span></div>
            <div class="def-row"><span class="def-key">Interpretation</span><span>±0.2pp is measurement noise; &gt;0.5pp is a material impulse; &gt;1.0pp is policy-relevant (delays rate cuts or triggers hike debates). The transmission channel differs by region: fast retail fuel pass-through in transport-heavy consumption baskets (US) vs. gas and electricity pass-through where gas sets marginal power prices (EU). A rising headline with a flat core confirms a first-round supply shock with anchored expectations.</span></div>
            <div class="def-row"><span class="def-key">Data sources</span><span>BLS CPI (US), Eurostat HICP flash (euro area), energy component weights, structural model estimates.</span></div>
            <div class="def-row"><span class="def-key">Frequency</span><span>Monthly, following statistical releases.</span></div>
            <div class="def-row"><span class="def-key">Iran 2026</span><span>US ≈ +0.6pp headline / +0.2pp core for a one-quarter closure (Kilian et al.); realized US headline reached 4.2% in May with core at 2.9%. Euro area ≈ +0.5pp; HICP 3.2% May easing to 2.8% June with core at 2.4%.</span></div>
          </div>
        </div>

        <!-- EXTENDED INDICATOR 7: GAS PRICE DEVIATION -->
        <div class="card">
          <h3>Gas Price Deviation Index (TTF) <span class="badge low">Real data</span></h3>
          <div class="chart-box" style="height:200px;"><canvas id="hist-gpdi"></canvas></div>
          <span class="src">Dutch TTF monthly averages (ICE benchmark, compiled from published figures) ÷ pre-2026-event baseline (~€35/MWh) × 100. The dominant feature is the 2022 European gas crisis: the August 2022 peak (~€236/MWh, index ~674) dwarfs the 2026 shock (index ~177 at the March peak), which is why gas needs its own deviation index rather than inheriting the oil one.</span>
          <div class="skill-panel">
            <div class="skill-head"><span class="sk-label">Predictive skill · computed backtest, overall hit rate</span><span class="sk-val" id="skval-gpdi">&ndash;</span></div>
            <div class="skill-box"><canvas id="skill-gpdi"></canvas></div>
            <span class="src">Target: next-month TTF direction. Rule: if the index moved ≥10 points over the past two months, predict the same direction. As with oil, price momentum alone carries little forward information; the panel exists to prove that honestly.</span>
          </div>
          <div class="def-block">
            <div class="def-row"><span class="def-key">Definition</span><span><code>GPDI(t) = TTF(t) / TTF(baseline) × 100</code>, the gas-market twin of the Price Deviation Index. Oil and gas must be tracked separately because their shocks decouple: 2022 was primarily a gas crisis in Europe, 2026 primarily an oil crisis globally with a gas component (Ras Laffan).</span></div>
            <div class="def-row"><span class="def-key">Interpretation</span><span>Same bands as the oil index (110 material, 140 severe), but gas amplitudes run far higher because storage, not rerouting, is the only buffer.</span></div>
            <div class="def-row"><span class="def-key">Data sources</span><span>ICE Dutch TTF front-month settlements, monthly averages; public via exchange summaries and Eurostat energy statistics.</span></div>
            <div class="def-row"><span class="def-key">Frequency</span><span>Daily during active situations; monthly otherwise.</span></div>
            <div class="def-row"><span class="def-key">Iran 2026</span><span>TTF nearly doubled to over €60/MWh by mid-March (index ~177) against 30% storage; easing since as the MoU holds, but the Ras Laffan capacity loss keeps a multi-year floor.</span></div>
          </div>
        </div>

        <!-- EXTENDED INDICATOR 8: GEOPOLITICAL RISK INDEX -->
        <div class="card">
          <h3>Geopolitical Risk Index (GPR) <span class="badge low">Real data</span></h3>
          <div class="chart-box" style="height:200px;"><canvas id="hist-gpr"></canvas></div>
          <span class="src">Caldara-Iacoviello GPR index (monthly, 100 = 1985&ndash;2019 average), a peer-reviewed, publicly downloadable series built from newspaper coverage of geopolitical tensions. Clear spikes at the February 2022 invasion (~350), October 2023, June 2025, and the February&ndash;March 2026 Iran war (~380), the highest reading of the window.</span>
          <div class="skill-panel">
            <div class="skill-head"><span class="sk-label">Predictive skill · computed backtest, overall hit rate</span><span class="sk-val" id="skval-gpr">&ndash;</span></div>
            <div class="skill-box"><canvas id="skill-gpr"></canvas></div>
            <span class="src">Target: next-month Brent direction. Rule: signals only when GPR is elevated (≥150); rising GPR predicts Brent up, falling GPR predicts down. The academic literature (Caldara &amp; Iacoviello 2022, AER) finds GPR shocks raise oil prices with a lag, which is what the rule operationalizes.</span>
