            <div class="def-row"><span class="def-key">Iran 2026</span><span>~30 points below norm at the spring 2026 trough (fill ~30% after the harsh winter), the reason the Qatari LNG loss transmitted so violently into TTF and euro area HICP energy (+10.8% YoY in May).</span></div>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>

      <h2 class="section-title">Design Principles</h2>
      <div class="grid g3">
        <div class="card">
          <h3>Falsifiability</h3>
          <p>Every method must state in advance what evidence would prove it wrong. A physical-balance thesis is falsified by inventory data; a risk-premium thesis by option-implied probabilities; a scenario probability by trigger events. Analysis that cannot fail is narrative, not science.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="card">
          <h3>Methodological Triangulation</h3>
          <p>Five independent lenses are applied to the same situation. Agreement across methods raises confidence; disagreement is reported as uncertainty, never averaged away. The dispersion of the five signals is itself a published output of the framework.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="card">
          <h3>Reproducibility</h3>
          <p>Each indicator has a documented definition, data source and update frequency, so two independent analysts applying the framework to the same situation reach the same readings. All revisions to scenario probabilities are logged with their trigger.</p>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="disclaimer">
        <b>Important:</b> This framework produces scenario illustrations synthesized from published analyst research and official statistics. Outputs are not verified forecasts, not investment recommendations, and not financial advice. Where sources conflict, ranges are shown.
      </div>
    </section>

    <!-- ============================================================ METHODS -->
    <section class="tab-panel" id="tab-methods">
      <h2 class="section-title">Five Scientific Methods for Analyzing Any Energy Situation</h2>
      <p class="lede">
        The five methods form a taxonomy spanning the main approaches in the energy economics literature and market practice: (1) <b>bottom-up physical accounting</b>, (2) the <b>event-study</b> approach to the risk premium, (3) <b>market-based expectations</b> from the futures term structure, (4) <b>structural macroeconometric modeling</b>, and (5) <b>probabilistic scenario integration</b>. Each card is structured along the scientific method: theoretical foundation, testable hypothesis, data, model, empirical validation (using Iran 2026), and known limitations. The methods are crisis-agnostic; only the input data change per situation.
      </p>

      <div class="grid g2">

        <!-- METHOD 1 -->
        <div class="card method-card">
          <div class="m-num">1</div>
          <span class="method-tag">Bottom-Up Physical Accounting</span>
          <h3>Supply-Demand Balance &amp; Flow Monitoring</h3>
          <div class="sm-step"><span class="sm-key">Foundation</span><span>Mass-balance identity: supply minus demand equals inventory change. Price adjusts until the physical deficit clears, buffered by stocks. The method underlying IEA and EIA balance tables.</span></div>
          <div class="sm-step"><span class="sm-key">Hypothesis</span><span>"The disruption removes X mb/d for Y weeks; bypass capacity replaces Z; the residual deficit draws inventories at rate D."</span></div>
          <div class="sm-step"><span class="sm-key">Data</span><span>Satellite/AIS transit counts (Kpler, Windward), production and export statistics, spare capacity, pipeline throughput, inventory levels.</span></div>
          <div class="sm-step"><span class="sm-key">Model</span><span>Weekly balance table; days-of-cover metric; deficit-to-price elasticity from historical episodes.</span></div>
          <div class="sm-step"><span class="sm-key">Validation (Iran 2026)</span><span>Correctly sized the shock: 10&ndash;14 mb/d stranded vs. only ~2.6 mb/d pipeline bypass predicted a severe draw, which materialized. Transit-count data led price at every turning point.</span></div>
          <div class="sm-step"><span class="sm-key">Limitations</span><span>Falsified by inventory data; slow to capture purely political shocks that never touch physical flows.</span></div>
          <div class="signal-row"><span class="sig-label">Output</span><span class="sig-val sig-neut">Physical deficit estimate + days-of-cover trajectory</span></div>
        </div>

        <!-- METHOD 2 -->
        <div class="card method-card">
          <div class="m-num">2</div>
          <span class="method-tag">Event-Study Approach</span>
          <h3>Geopolitical Risk Premium Decomposition</h3>
          <div class="sm-step"><span class="sm-key">Foundation</span><span>Efficient-markets event-study logic: price changes in narrow windows around discrete, exogenous events isolate the market's valuation of the event itself, separating a fundamentals component from a risk premium residual.</span></div>
          <div class="sm-step"><span class="sm-key">Hypothesis</span><span>"The premium embedded in the current price is P dollars; it decays at rate R absent new events and re-inflates on trigger events."</span></div>
          <div class="sm-step"><span class="sm-key">Data</span><span>High-frequency prices around timestamped events; a rolling fundamentals-implied price from Method 1.</span></div>
          <div class="sm-step"><span class="sm-key">Model</span><span>Premium = spot minus fundamentals-implied price; event regression of returns on event dummies.</span></div>
          <div class="sm-step"><span class="sm-key">Validation (Iran 2026)</span><span>Goldman Sachs quantified a ~$14/bbl premium on day three. The premium proved highly event-elastic: +8% at outbreak, &minus;11% on a reopening statement, &minus;15% in one day on the ceasefire, re-inflating each time implementation lagged announcements.</span></div>
          <div class="sm-step"><span class="sm-key">Limitations</span><span>Identifies the size of the premium, not the timing of the next trigger; assumes events are exogenous and well-timestamped.</span></div>
          <div class="signal-row"><span class="sig-label">Output</span><span class="sig-val sig-neut">Current premium estimate + asymmetry of tail risk</span></div>
        </div>

        <!-- METHOD 3 -->
        <div class="card method-card">
          <div class="m-num">3</div>
          <span class="method-tag">Market-Based Expectations</span>
          <h3>Futures Term Structure &amp; Options Analysis</h3>
          <div class="sm-step"><span class="sm-key">Foundation</span><span>Theory of storage: backwardation (spot above deferred) signals physical scarcity; contango signals surplus. Option-implied volatility and skew reveal the probability mass the market assigns to tails.</span></div>
          <div class="sm-step"><span class="sm-key">Hypothesis</span><span>"The curve shape implies the market expects normalization within N months; the options market prices a tail probability of Q for renewed disruption."</span></div>
          <div class="sm-step"><span class="sm-key">Data</span><span>Full futures curve, implied volatility surface, call/put skew, open interest.</span></div>
          <div class="sm-step"><span class="sm-key">Model</span><span>Front-to-deferred spreads, curve slope percentile vs. history, risk-neutral density estimation from options.</span></div>
          <div class="sm-step"><span class="sm-key">Validation (Iran 2026)</span><span>Record backwardation correctly flagged acute tightness in March&ndash;April. The later configuration of a falling spot with persistent call skew ("calm price, nervous options") correctly signaled that normalization optimism was fragile.</span></div>
          <div class="sm-step"><span class="sm-key">Limitations</span><span>The key caveat from the academic literature (Kilian et al.): futures prices are hedging prices, not unbiased expectations of the future spot price. A downward-sloping curve is necessary but not sufficient evidence that the worst is over. The method is also reflexive; it reads the crowd it is part of.</span></div>
          <div class="signal-row"><span class="sig-label">Output</span><span class="sig-val sig-neut">Implied normalization timeline + tail-risk pricing</span></div>
        </div>

        <!-- METHOD 4 -->
        <div class="card method-card">
          <div class="m-num">4</div>
          <span class="method-tag">Structural Macroeconometrics</span>
          <h3>Macro Transmission Modeling</h3>
          <div class="sm-step"><span class="sm-key">Foundation</span><span>Structural models of how energy price shocks transmit to inflation, growth and policy. State of the art: calibrated nonlinear DSGE models of the global oil market feeding structural VAR models of fuel-price pass-through (Kilian, Plante, Richter &amp; Zhou 2026, Dallas Fed WP 26-09), a formal alternative to rule-of-thumb elasticities.</span></div>
          <div class="sm-step"><span class="sm-key">Hypothesis</span><span>"A disruption of duration D adds H percentage points to headline inflation and C to core, per region, with long-run expectations remaining anchored."</span></div>
          <div class="sm-step"><span class="sm-key">Data</span><span>CPI/HICP by component, retail fuel prices, gas benchmarks, storage levels, central bank communications, published elasticities.</span></div>
          <div class="sm-step"><span class="sm-key">Model</span><span>Region-specific transmission channels: fast fuel-price pass-through in transport-heavy consumption baskets; gas-and-electricity pass-through where power markets set marginal prices.</span></div>
          <div class="sm-step"><span class="sm-key">Validation (Iran 2026)</span><span>Model and data agree. <b>United States:</b> headline CPI accelerated 3.3% &rarr; 3.8% &rarr; 4.2% (Mar&ndash;May, BLS), energy +23.5% and gasoline +40.5% YoY, while core rose only 2.6% &rarr; 2.8% &rarr; 2.9%; Kilian et al. estimate ≈+0.6pp headline / +0.2pp core for a one-quarter closure, with near-zero movement in long-run expectations, broadly the anchored pattern observed. <b>Europe (euro area):</b> transmission ran through gas and oil, with TTF nearly doubling to over €60/MWh against ~30% storage; HICP rose from 1.7% in January to 3.2% in May (energy +10.8%) and eased to 2.8% in June (energy 8.7%, Eurostat flash); core moved from 2.2% to 2.6% and back to 2.4%. The ECB postponed rate cuts on 19 March and warns of technical recession risk in Germany and Italy; Germany's growth forecast was cut to 0.6%. In both regions the shock is predominantly a first-round energy effect, though US services (airfares +26.7% YoY) and euro area services (3.5% in May) show early second-round pressure worth monitoring.</span></div>
          <div class="sm-step"><span class="sm-key">Limitations</span><span>Long transmission lags; elasticities estimated on past episodes may not hold under unprecedented disruptions; regional heterogeneity requires separate calibration per economy.</span></div>
          <div class="signal-row"><span class="sig-label">Output</span><span class="sig-val sig-neut">Regional inflation impulse + growth drag + policy reaction path</span></div>
        </div>

        <!-- METHOD 5 -->
        <div class="card method-card" style="grid-column: 1 / -1;">
          <div class="m-num">5</div>
          <span class="method-tag">Probabilistic Integration</span>
          <h3>Scenario &amp; Probability-Weighted Analysis</h3>
          <div class="sm-step"><span class="sm-key">Foundation</span><span>Decision analysis under uncertainty: mutually exclusive, collectively exhaustive scenarios with explicit prior probabilities; Bayesian updating against pre-specified triggers. This method integrates the evidence of Methods 1&ndash;4 into a single probability-weighted expectation.</span></div>
          <div class="sm-step"><span class="sm-key">Hypothesis</span><span>"Given the current evidence, scenario probabilities are (pA, pB, pC); the probability-weighted path is E. Trigger T shifts probability mass from A to C."</span></div>
          <div class="sm-step"><span class="sm-key">Validation (Iran 2026)</span><span>Announcement-driven prices whipsawed repeatedly (ceasefires announced, then violated). A disciplined trigger-based updating rule outperformed headline-reactive judgment throughout the episode.</span></div>
          <div class="sm-step"><span class="sm-key">Limitations</span><span>Prior probabilities are structured judgments, not measurements; the framework mitigates this by making them explicit, adjustable and logged.</span></div>
          <div class="grid g3 mt">
            <div class="card scen bull">
              <span class="badge low">Template A</span>
              <h3 class="mt">Normalization</h3>
              <ul>
                <li>Disruption resolved; flows return toward baseline within the horizon</li>
                <li>Price Deviation Index decays toward 100</li>
                <li>Risk premium compresses; policy pressure eases</li>
              </ul>
            </div>
            <div class="card scen base">
              <span class="badge med">Template B</span>
              <h3 class="mt">Constrained Flow</h3>
              <ul>
                <li>Partial, conditioned or politically leveraged supply</li>
                <li>Index oscillates in an elevated band on headlines</li>
                <li>Persistent premium; elevated logistics and insurance costs</li>
              </ul>
            </div>
            <div class="card scen bear">
              <span class="badge high">Template C</span>
              <h3 class="mt">Escalation</h3>
              <ul>
                <li>Disruption widens or re-triggers; supply loss deepens</li>
                <li>Index breaks above the prior peak; demand destruction begins</li>
                <li>Recession thresholds approached in import-dependent economies</li>
              </ul>
            </div>
          </div>
          <div class="signal-row mt"><span class="sig-label">Output</span><span class="sig-val sig-neut">Probability-weighted expectation path, operationalized in the Scenario Engine tab</span></div>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="card mt">
        <h3>Method Comparison Matrix</h3>
        <table>
          <thead><tr><th>Method</th><th>Epistemic Type</th><th>Primary Data</th><th>Falsified By</th><th>Blind Spot</th></tr></thead>
          <tbody>
            <tr><td><b>1 · Physical accounting</b></td><td>Deterministic identity</td><td>Flows, inventories, capacities</td><td>Inventory and transit data</td><td>Political shocks without physical footprint</td></tr>
            <tr><td><b>2 · Event study</b></td><td>Empirical decomposition</td><td>High-frequency prices, event log</td><td>Premium fails to move on true events</td><td>Cannot time the next trigger</td></tr>
            <tr><td><b>3 · Term structure</b></td><td>Market-implied inference</td><td>Futures curve, options surface</td><td>Realized path diverges from implied path</td><td>Reflexive; hedging prices ≠ expectations</td></tr>
            <tr><td><b>4 · Macro transmission</b></td><td>Structural model</td><td>CPI/HICP, fuel and gas prices, elasticities</td><td>Realized inflation vs. modeled impulse</td><td>Long lags; regime dependence</td></tr>
            <tr><td><b>5 · Scenario integration</b></td><td>Probabilistic synthesis</td><td>Outputs of Methods 1&ndash;4 + triggers</td><td>Systematic forecast error at checkpoints</td><td>Priors are judgments</td></tr>
          </tbody>
        </table>
        <span class="src">Triangulation rule: agreement across ≥3 independent methods constitutes a robust signal; a 3&ndash;2 split is reported as elevated uncertainty, never averaged into false precision.</span>
      </div>
    </section>

