    <!-- ============================================================ MONITORS -->
    <section class="tab-panel" id="tab-monitors">
      <h2 class="section-title">Standing Early-Warning Monitors</h2>
      <p class="lede">
        Five permanent monitors implement step 1 of the scientific workflow (Observe) continuously, so that when the next situation begins, the baseline data already exist. They apply to any geography: maritime chokepoints, pipeline corridors, LNG terminals, refining hubs or grid infrastructure, and to any trigger: conflict, sanctions, technical failure, cyber incident or extreme weather.
      </p>

      <div class="grid g3">
        <div class="card">
          <span class="method-tag">Monitor 1</span>
          <h3>Chokepoint Flow Tracker</h3>
          <p>Standing watchlist of the six global maritime chokepoints (Hormuz ~20 mb/d, Malacca ~24, Suez/SUMED ~9, Bab el-Mandeb ~9, Danish Straits, Panama) plus major pipeline corridors. Alert rule: transit-count deviation &gt;20% from the trailing 30-day mean.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="card">
          <span class="method-tag">Monitor 2</span>
          <h3>Risk Premium Gauge</h3>
          <p>Maintains a rolling fundamentals-implied price (inventories, spare capacity, demand) and reads the spread to spot as the geopolitical or event premium. Alert rule: premium doubles within five sessions.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="card">
          <span class="method-tag">Monitor 3</span>
          <h3>Term Structure &amp; Volatility Screen</h3>
          <p>Daily screen of front-to-deferred spreads, implied-volatility percentile and call skew. Alert rule: the "calm price, nervous options" configuration, a falling spot with persistent tail pricing, flags underpriced re-escalation risk.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="card">
          <span class="method-tag">Monitor 4</span>
          <h3>Macro Damage Estimator</h3>
          <p>Pre-loaded elasticity table (inflation and growth response per 10% energy price move, per region and channel: fuel vs. gas/power) so day-one impact estimates are mechanical, not improvised. Tracks second-round channels: fertilizer, food, freight, aviation.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="card">
          <span class="method-tag">Monitor 5</span>
          <h3>Scenario Book</h3>
          <p>Three living scenario templates (Normalization / Constrained Flow / Escalation) with explicit probabilities and the trigger catalogue for updating them. The probability-weighted path is published at a fixed weekly cadence.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="card" style="background: linear-gradient(160deg, var(--mp-dark), var(--mp-darker)); color:#fff; border:none;">
          <span class="method-tag" style="background:rgba(248,169,58,0.2); color:var(--mp-orange);">Structural Overlay</span>
          <h3 style="color:#fff;">Transition Acceleration Tracker</h3>
          <p style="color:rgba(255,255,255,0.85);">Every fossil supply crisis accelerates electrification and demand-side substitution. The monitor tracks EV sales, renewables investment and efficiency policy after each shock, because demand destruction is increasingly permanent rather than cyclical, which lowers the price path of every subsequent crisis.</p>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="card mt">
        <h3>Crisis Severity Scorecard (Apply to Any Event)</h3>
        <table>
          <thead><tr><th>Dimension</th><th>Question</th><th>Scale</th><th>Weight</th></tr></thead>
          <tbody>
            <tr><td><b>Volume at risk</b></td><td>Share of global supply affected?</td><td>1 = &lt;2% &nbsp;·&nbsp; 5 = &gt;15%</td><td>30%</td></tr>
            <tr><td><b>Redundancy</b></td><td>Bypass routes and spare capacity available?</td><td>1 = fully reroutable &nbsp;·&nbsp; 5 = no alternative</td><td>25%</td></tr>
            <tr><td><b>Duration risk</b></td><td>Can the disruption persist for months?</td><td>1 = days &nbsp;·&nbsp; 5 = multi-year (infrastructure damage)</td><td>20%</td></tr>
            <tr><td><b>Escalation optionality</b></td><td>Can one actor re-trigger the disruption cheaply?</td><td>1 = one-off event &nbsp;·&nbsp; 5 = unilateral switch</td><td>15%</td></tr>
            <tr><td><b>Second-round breadth</b></td><td>Food, fertilizer, freight, aviation exposure?</td><td>1 = contained &nbsp;·&nbsp; 5 = all channels active</td><td>10%</td></tr>
          </tbody>
        </table>
        <span class="src">Weighted score ≥4.0 designates a systemic event requiring full framework activation and weekly publication cadence. Reference calibration: Iran 2026 scored 4.55 (see Case Study).</span>
      </div>
    </section>

